For example, if we build an 1-gram model from the words "act" and "ace", our model would capture the fact that "c" always follows "a" (based on the data we have seen). For example, row 3 corresponds to the 3rd letter in the alphabet - "c" - and will contain a list of counts of how often each other letter followed "c". After we have our counts, for each letter in the table, we just have to convert each row to a probability distribution and return them!

Build an n-gram model for autocompletion where n=1
An n-gram model is a language model that can be used to build an autocompletion system. An n-gram model keeps track of the next letter given the previous "n" letters.
If n=1, then you are simply keeping track of the next letter given the previous letter.
For example, if we build an 1-gram model from the words "act" and "ace", our model would capture the fact that "c" always follows "a" (based on the data we have seen). It would also learn that "t" follows "c" half the time otherwise it is "e".
To build our 1-gram model, we simply need to count up how often each letter occurs given the current letter. That is, we can just keep a 26x26 table where each row contains the counts of the words following the row index. For example, row 3 corresponds to the 3rd letter in the alphabet - "c" - and will contain a list of counts of how often each other letter followed "c".
After we have our counts, for each letter in the table, we just have to convert each row to a probability distribution and return them!

An n-gram model is a language model that can be used to build an autocompletion system. An n-gram model keeps track of the next letter given the previous "n" letters.
If n=1, then you are simply keeping track of the next letter given the previous letter.
For example, if we build an 1-gram model from the words "act" and "ace", our model would capture the fact that "c" always follows "a" (based on the data we have seen). It would also learn that "t" follows "c" half the time otherwise it is "e".
To build our 1-gram model, we simply need to count up how often each letter occurs given the current letter. That is, we can just keep a 26x26 table where each row contains the counts of the words following the row index. For example, row 3 corresponds to the 3rd letter in the alphabet - "c" - and will contain a list of counts of how often each other letter followed "c".
After we have our counts, for each letter in the table, we just have to convert each row to a probability distribution and return them!

An n-gram model is a language model that can be used to build an autocompletion system. An n-gram model keeps track of the next letter given the previous "n" letters.
If n=1, then you are simply keeping track of the next letter given the previous letter.
For example, if we build an 1-gram model from the words "act" and "ace", our model would capture the fact that "c" always follows "a" (based on the data we have seen). It would also learn that "t" follows "c" half the time otherwise it is "e".
To build our 1-gram model, we simply need to count up how often each letter occurs given the current letter. That is, we can just keep a 26x26 table where each row contains the counts of the words following the row index. For example, row 3 corresponds to the 3rd letter in the alphabet - "c" - and will contain a list of counts of how often each other letter followed "c".
After we have our counts, for each letter in the table, we just have to convert each row to a probability distribution and return them!
